00:59:36,620 --> 00:59:41,420
estrogen alone that we would hang our hat on. There was one paper that came out that actually

597
00:59:41,420 --> 00:59:48,860
showed a 30% significant decrease, but that didn't hold up in subsequent papers. So let's

598
00:59:48,860 --> 00:59:55,500
say there's no increased risk with estrogen alone. With estrogen and progesterone, there was a reported

599
00:59:55,500 --> 01:00:03,660
26% increase. And it's important that we understand what that is. First, that was not statistically

600
01:00:03,660 --> 01:00:10,540
significant so that by scientific standards, we think that could have been caused by chance alone.

601
01:00:10,540 --> 01:00:13,260
What was the P value? I don't remember the P value.

602
01:00:13,260 --> 01:00:17,180
But you're saying it was definitely below. It was above 0.5.

603
01:00:17,180 --> 01:00:24,540
Yes, it wasn't statistically significant. But in order for there to be a 26% increase,

604
01:00:25,100 --> 01:00:34,860
you have to know what the actual risk in numbers was for women who got the estrogen plus progesterone.

605
01:00:34,860 --> 01:00:39,260
So let's hit pause and explain absolute. Yeah, you're going to explain absolute versus relative.

606
01:00:39,820 --> 01:00:46,780
You're comparing the incidence among women who took the two hormones compared to women

607
01:00:46,780 --> 01:00:54,700
who were randomized to a placebo. And there was this 26% reported increase. Now, you could have

608
01:00:54,700 --> 01:01:03,900
a 26% reported increase if you have a real increase in risk or if your control, the women

609
01:01:03,900 --> 01:01:11,020
who were randomized to placebo had a lower than expected risk of breast cancer. And in fact,

610
01:01:11,020 --> 01:01:16,860
when you look at those numbers, you find that when you compare the women who were randomized

611
01:01:16,860 --> 01:01:25,020
to the two hormones compared with the women who were randomized to placebo on the estrogen only

612
01:01:25,020 --> 01:01:31,820
arm, there was no increased risk even among the women who were randomized to the two hormones.

613
01:01:31,820 --> 01:01:40,460
It was because there was a lower than expected risk among the control group who were randomized

614
01:01:40,460 --> 01:01:46,300
to the two hormones that you had what looked like an increased risk, not a statistically

615
01:01:46,300 --> 01:01:52,380
significant one, but an increased risk. What's the best explanation for that? Is there one? Yes.

616
01:01:52,380 --> 01:02:04,140
The women who had taken hormones before being randomized on the study, who were randomized to

617
01:02:04,140 --> 01:02:13,740
placebo, had a lower expected risk of breast cancer than women who had never taken hormones.

618
01:02:13,740 --> 01:02:21,980
If you take the women who had taken hormones before going on the study and remove them from

619
01:02:21,980 --> 01:02:29,020
the control group, you find no increased risk when you compare the women who got the hormones

620
01:02:29,020 --> 01:02:36,460
with the residual women in the control group. So the women who were taking hormones before the study

621
01:02:37,100 --> 01:02:44,300
had a lower than expected risk of eventual breast cancer. They lowered the control group number,

622
01:02:45,180 --> 01:02:51,660
and they gave you this artificial increased risk that you saw among the women who took the two

623
01:02:51,660 --> 01:02:58,220
hormones. Is that clear? Of course, it's always hard to make that clear. That's an example of the

624
01:02:58,220 --> 01:03:06,620
kind of data manipulation that went on to try to create the impression of a real finding that really

625
01:03:06,620 --> 01:03:11,420
was not there. But Peter, to your question about absolute and relative risks, that's what's crucial

626
01:03:11,420 --> 01:03:20,540
here. If I say that eating a grapefruit doubles my risk of bunions, I need to know what numbers

627
01:03:20,620 --> 01:03:26,860
we're talking about. If the numbers jump from one person to two person out of a hundred or out of a

628
01:03:26,860 --> 01:03:32,700
thousand, that's not a very big... I can say it's doubling the risk, but it's trivial. But if the

629
01:03:32,700 --> 01:03:37,820
numbers double from 500 to a thousand in a group of 10,000, then we might have a finding we should

630
01:03:37,820 --> 01:03:45,020
be paying attention to. Most studies, epidemiologists, of course, report relative risks where we don't

631
01:03:45,020 --> 01:03:49,500
even know. In some cases, we don't even know what the absolute numbers are. Abram and I were at

632
01:03:49,500 --> 01:03:58,460
pains in our book to see when we would read studies that reported an increased risk of X, Y, or Z,

633
01:03:58,460 --> 01:04:03,660
or a reduced risk of something, to see what the absolute numbers were. Are we talking about

634
01:04:03,660 --> 01:04:09,660
outliers? Are we talking about a finding that's really statistically strong as well as significant?

635
01:04:09,660 --> 01:04:14,300
And in many cases, we couldn't even find what the absolute numbers were. But where we could, we

