01:05:13,900 --> 01:05:18,300
you statistically. And against that is what are the benefits to you?

647
01:05:18,300 --> 01:05:26,300
Well, that's the point. Absolutely. But even talking about those risks, which we don't accept

648
01:05:26,300 --> 01:05:32,060
as real, and there were other studies like the Nurses Health Study that, as I mentioned earlier,

649
01:05:32,060 --> 01:05:38,540
showed that there is no increased risk of breast cancer with hormones taken for 5, 10, or 15 years.

650
01:05:39,340 --> 01:05:46,940
Even assuming those risks, we know that women who were diagnosed with breast cancer while on

651
01:05:46,940 --> 01:05:55,260
hormones have a better prognosis, stage for stage, than women who were diagnosed not taking hormones.

652
01:05:55,260 --> 01:06:01,180
And even the Women's Health Initiative, in one of the subsequent papers, said that the women who

653
01:06:01,180 --> 01:06:08,140
had been randomized to hormones and have gotten breast cancer had a lower risk of dying from

654
01:06:08,220 --> 01:06:12,460
breast cancer than the control group that didn't get hormones.

655
01:06:12,460 --> 01:06:18,140
This is huge. This is such an important thing for physicians and for women to understand,

656
01:06:18,140 --> 01:06:23,980
and it seems so counterintuitive. Women who've had breast cancer, who are on HRT,

657
01:06:24,700 --> 01:06:27,820
have a better prognosis. This is astonishing.

658
01:06:27,820 --> 01:06:32,860
And what's interesting about it is you can dismiss the Nurses Health Study on that because of the

659
01:06:32,860 --> 01:06:39,100
healthy user bias that goes into it. It is easy to say, and I think it's a legitimate criticism,

660
01:06:39,100 --> 01:06:43,100
that the women in the Nurses Health Study who had better outcomes, of course they had better

661
01:06:43,100 --> 01:06:48,940
outcomes. They were more health conscious. They were nurses. They were selected through that

662
01:06:48,940 --> 01:06:53,740
process to be that way. So the proponent of the Women's Health Initiative will say it's a better

663
01:06:53,740 --> 01:06:58,940
study because it was randomized, notwithstanding the limitations of that. But it's interesting

664
01:06:58,940 --> 01:07:03,020
that in this subset analysis, which is always fraught with its own statistical issues,

665
01:07:03,660 --> 01:07:08,620
the finding of the Nurses Health Study with respect to this point you make still held up.

666
01:07:08,620 --> 01:07:16,060
That is to say, I'll repeat it because it is so important, a woman who is on HRT at the time of

667
01:07:16,060 --> 01:07:22,780
breast cancer diagnosis has a lower rate of mortality, not just all cause, but breast cancer,

668
01:07:22,780 --> 01:07:27,420
if I'm correct. Yes. And if we amplify that just a little,

669
01:07:28,140 --> 01:07:36,060
hormones have been used, estrogen specifically, has been used to treat breast cancer. And there

670
01:07:36,060 --> 01:07:42,540
have been significant favorable responses. I can't imagine treating lung cancer by increasing the

671
01:07:42,540 --> 01:07:50,380
number of cigarettes you smoke every day. And yet, as early as 1944, there were researchers

672
01:07:50,380 --> 01:07:58,380
publishing a 25% response rate among patients with measurable breast cancer who were treated

673
01:07:58,380 --> 01:08:07,420
with estrogen. If a woman gets pregnant after breast cancer, flooding her body with estrogen,

674
01:08:08,060 --> 01:08:15,020
and we used to advise women never to do that, and women disregarded our advice, the pregnancy

675
01:08:15,020 --> 01:08:22,380
does not increase the risk of breast cancer coming back. If anything, it decreases the risk

676
01:08:22,380 --> 01:08:28,460
of cancer coming back. This is what I find so important and so fascinating, which is the heart

677
01:08:28,460 --> 01:08:36,540
of this discussion is to try to puncture the widespread premise that estrogen causes breast

678
01:08:36,540 --> 01:08:44,220
cancer. And that's, of course, the great fear, but it's just an embedded assumption. And here,

679
01:08:44,220 --> 01:08:50,540
as Avram has just described, research from treating women with breast cancer, or women

680
01:08:50,540 --> 01:08:56,300
who are pregnant, or women who began menstruating very early, the many directions we might look at

681
01:08:56,300 --> 01:09:02,060
women on birth control pills, do any of those things that increase the amount of estrogen in

682
01:09:02,060 --> 01:09:07,420
your body, is that related in some way to breast cancer? And it is not. That's the key.

683
01:09:07,420 --> 01:09:10,620
So another interesting aspect of looking at the Women's Health Initiative,

684
01:09:10,620 --> 01:09:15,740
which it's very hard to look at the data and not ask the question, what is the role of MPA?

685
01:09:16,700 --> 01:09:22,700
Because when you look at the women who had a uterus, these are women who got estrogen and

686
01:09:22,700 --> 01:09:29,020
progesterone, synthetic progesterone, progestin, versus placebo, there was a trend towards a higher

687
01:09:29,580 --> 01:09:35,740
breast cancer. But when you look at the opposite, the women who had no uterus, and therefore only

688
01:09:35,740 --> 01:09:41,660
needed estrogen, the trend was in the exact opposite direction to the exact same magnitude.

689
01:09:41,660 --> 01:09:46,700
I mean, it almost looks like you couldn't make it up. There are, they are mirror images of each

690
01:09:46,700 --> 01:09:52,620
other. So you have to ask the question, what are the differences? And there are two. One of them

691
01:09:52,620 --> 01:09:58,780
had a uterus, one did not, and one took synthetic progestin and one did not. So the question is,

692
01:09:58,780 --> 01:10:05,580
does not having a uterus and or does taking synthetic progesterone make a difference?

693
01:10:05,900 --> 01:10:12,620
First on the synthetic progesterone, it's MPA, medroxyprogesterone acetate, which was used

694
01:10:12,620 --> 01:10:18,700
in the Women's Health Initiative because that was the most widely prescribed progesterone available

695
01:10:18,700 --> 01:10:25,500
in the United States. First, let me go back to saying that the increased risk seen with the

696
01:10:25,500 --> 01:10:33,100
combination was not statistically significant, did not hold up, and was due largely to a problem

697
01:10:33,100 --> 01:10:38,940
with the control group. If you accept that, anything we say at this point is…

698
01:10:38,940 --> 01:10:39,740
Speculation.

699
01:10:39,740 --> 01:10:47,660
…and irrelevant, really, but I'll take your question. So what has resulted from that is people

700
01:10:47,660 --> 01:10:53,740
are saying, well, the problem really isn't estrogen. We'll give estrogen a pass. The problem

701
01:10:53,740 --> 01:11:01,020
is progesterone, and in fact, this particular synthetic progesterone. Well, I'm not sure

702
01:11:01,020 --> 01:11:07,660
there's a problem because the numbers don't really bear that out. But if there is a problem,

703
01:11:07,660 --> 01:11:17,580
there are now forms of progesterone which are not synthetic that are now being advised and used,

704
01:11:18,140 --> 01:11:26,060
and thus far have not been associated even with any finding of an increased risk of breast cancer.

705
01:11:26,060 --> 01:11:36,860
But in addition, progesterone also has been used to treat breast cancer, and progesterone works

706
01:11:36,860 --> 01:11:45,100
as well as tamoxifen does to treat breast cancer. In a randomized trial comparing tamoxifen

707
01:11:45,100 --> 01:11:51,740
to progesterone, in the early 70s when tamoxifen was first produced and marketed,

708
01:11:51,740 --> 01:11:57,660
progesterone did a little better than tamoxifen, but because in the doses used,

709
01:11:57,660 --> 01:12:05,260
it was associated with increased fluid retention and women became nauseated, it lost out to

710
01:12:05,260 --> 01:12:13,820
tamoxifen. But it was used to treat breast cancer. There was a study that came out of India by an

711
01:12:13,820 --> 01:12:22,780
investigator trained in England who found that if he gave an injection of progesterone around

712
01:12:22,780 --> 01:12:31,340
the time of surgery to remove primary breast cancer, he significantly improved the prognosis,

713
01:12:31,340 --> 01:12:39,340
decreased the risk of recurrence. So making a lot of noise around progesterone doesn't really fit

714
01:12:39,900 --> 01:12:45,420
the available data that we have. So two things. One, I actually had a discussion with Joanne

715
01:12:45,420 --> 01:12:52,060
Manson about this a few years ago, which was why did you use that crappy estrogen in progestin?

716
01:12:52,060 --> 01:12:59,020
Why didn't you use what we would use today, which is bioidentical estrogen, bioidentical progesterone?

717
01:12:59,820 --> 01:13:03,340
And I've always had a lot of respect for Joanne, by the way. I don't know if you guys were able to,

718
01:13:03,900 --> 01:13:07,580
did you interview her for the book? I don't, yeah, I didn't think so. And she gave me an answer that

719
01:13:07,580 --> 01:13:11,100
I thought was very logical and you've alluded to it already. She said, you're probably right,

720
01:13:11,100 --> 01:13:17,820
Peter. I mean, I think the bioidentical hormones are likely better, but we had to do it with what

721
01:13:17,820 --> 01:13:24,220
was available in the, we had to test what was being used by the average physician at the time. And

722
01:13:24,220 --> 01:13:28,940
certainly people at the time were making some noise that shouldn't we at least use bioidentical human

723
01:13:28,940 --> 01:13:33,980
hormones, which intuitively makes more sense. But she said a study testing that wouldn't have made

724
01:13:33,980 --> 01:13:40,060
sense in the nineties because that wasn't what the average woman was being tested. So that said,

725
01:13:40,620 --> 01:13:45,660
most women today are using bioidentical progesterone, aren't they? When they're receiving

726
01:13:45,660 --> 01:13:50,060
hormone replacement therapy, they're still using synthetic progesterone? Well, first,

727
01:13:50,060 --> 01:13:55,980
Primerin. Yes. Let's talk about the estrogen. The word bioidentical is a buzzword. As you know,

728
01:13:55,980 --> 01:14:03,660
bioidentical really refers to estradiol, which is the leading circulating estrogen in a woman's body.

729
01:14:04,140 --> 01:14:12,780
And there are pharmaceutically prescribed estrogens that are made by significant manufacturers

730
01:14:12,780 --> 01:14:18,620
that we have no problem with. And I want to get back to that in a minute. But bioidentical is also

731
01:14:18,620 --> 01:14:26,140
used for what is prepared by pharmacists based on prescriptions written by local practitioners

732
01:14:26,700 --> 01:14:35,580
where quality control is lacking. There is no clear dose equivalency. And every responsible

733
01:14:35,580 --> 01:14:40,860
investigator I know wants to make the point that buying something because it's got the word

734
01:14:40,860 --> 01:14:48,780
bioidentical, which sounds comforting, is a mistake. Second, Primerin, which is pregnant

735
01:14:48,780 --> 01:14:55,820
mer urine, and I say that rubbing your face in it because it sounds so terrible, is the longest

736
01:14:55,820 --> 01:15:03,980
studied form of estrogen. And we now have 60 years of data with Primerin. And most of the studies that

737
01:15:03,980 --> 01:15:10,220
show the benefit for estrogen are studies that were done on Primerin for the same reason that

738
01:15:10,220 --> 01:15:17,820
Joanne Manson gave you. It's the one that was used most often. In addition, Primerin contains at least

739
01:15:17,820 --> 01:15:25,660
10 different forms of estrogen, including some that are the most beneficial forms of estrogen

740
01:15:25,660 --> 01:15:33,260
for brain health, which is not present in estradiol or estriol. So that my preference,

741
01:15:33,260 --> 01:15:40,780
based on data only, is Primerin because we have the most data supporting it. Now, as far as

742
01:15:40,780 --> 01:15:48,780
progesterone is concerned, yes, micronized bioidentical progesterone appears to be the

743
01:15:48,780 --> 01:15:53,820
safest form of progesterone administration. What do you think explains, this is a bit of a pivot,

744
01:15:53,820 --> 01:15:59,100
but what do you think explains the mechanism of action? So I'll take a step back and preface this

745
01:15:59,100 --> 01:16:04,380
with the following. You alluded to this earlier. Most people intuitively think testosterone must

746
01:16:04,380 --> 01:16:10,540
be driving prostate cancer. But the problem is men tend to get prostate cancer when their

747
01:16:10,540 --> 01:16:14,460
testosterone levels are at their lowest, not their highest. And men with high testosterone

748
01:16:14,460 --> 01:16:19,740
when they're young don't seem to get prostate cancer. So it's just a bit confusing. And in fact,

749
01:16:19,740 --> 01:16:23,420
there's more recent data to suggest that the lower the testosterone, the more likely the

750
01:16:23,420 --> 01:16:27,180
probability of a high grade prostate cancer. So everything seems to be moving in the wrong

751
01:16:27,180 --> 01:16:31,340
direction as testosterone goes down. May I just interrupt that it's the same with estrogen?

752
01:16:31,500 --> 01:16:31,660
Yes.

753
01:16:31,660 --> 01:16:35,900
As women get older and have lower estrogen levels, the rates of breast cancer increase.

754
01:16:35,900 --> 01:16:42,220
So therein lies my point. What do you think explains the mechanism by which estrogen

755
01:16:42,220 --> 01:16:48,300
withdrawal and or removal, and the same for progesterone, is increasing this risk? And why,

756
01:16:48,300 --> 01:16:55,420
Avram, can you point out these examples of administration of these things that seem to

757
01:16:55,980 --> 01:17:00,220
potentially improve the condition? What do you think is happening at the molecular level,

758
01:17:00,220 --> 01:17:03,980
acknowledging what you said at the outset, which is we don't have a goddamn clue what cancer is?

759
01:17:03,980 --> 01:17:09,260
We have clues, but I said I don't understand what cancer is. And the reason I said that right at

760
01:17:09,260 --> 01:17:14,460
the beginning is to try to forestall just this kind of question. The best answer I can give

761
01:17:14,460 --> 01:17:22,940
is we think we understand the environment that is friendly to a cancer, which is the environment

762
01:17:23,660 --> 01:17:30,540
in which the cancer develops. And we try to change that environment to make it less conducive

763
01:17:30,540 --> 01:17:36,860
to the continued growth of the cancer. That means in a low estrogen environment, you might use

764
01:17:36,860 --> 01:17:42,460
estrogen because that is now unfriendly to the cancer. In a high estrogen environment,

765
01:17:42,460 --> 01:17:48,540
you might remove estrogen. Same with testosterone. But exactly how that works,

766
01:17:49,420 --> 01:17:53,500
I would use a lot of fancy words and they would try to cover my ignorance.

767
01:17:54,460 --> 01:17:59,580
Appreciate the honesty. Most of us tend to use those fancy words and hide our ignorance behind them.

768
01:18:00,540 --> 01:18:08,060
So in 2002, the JAMA study comes out and there were a bunch of follow-ups. So there was a 2003,

769
01:18:08,060 --> 01:18:12,140
a 2004 follow-up. What did each of these follow-ups attempt to do?

770
01:18:12,140 --> 01:18:19,660
The 2002 follow-up said that the combination of estrogen and progesterone increases the risk

